[[Bhutan]] set up the program for the deaf in a hearing school in [[Thimbu]] ca. 2000, and the first dedicated school, in [[Paro, Bhutan|Paro]], was approved in 2013.<ref>[http://www.gallaudet.edu/news/bhutan_.html]</ref> Part of government funding for deaf education includes developing '''Bhutanese Sign Language''' as the language of instruction. Development includes at least creating vocabulary for technical subjects,<ref>[http://georgem.co.tz/showthread.php?t=938]</ref> and deciding on which regional signs to use where they differ.<ref>[http://www.deaftoday.com/news/archives/2003/05/bhutan_to_begin.html]</ref> It is not clear if there are multiple sign languages in Bhutan, or merely local differences in vocabulary. It is unknown whether Bhutanese Sign Language is related to the [[Indian Sign Language|Indian]] or [[Nepali Sign Language|Nepali]] sign languages.<ref>[http://joshuaproject.net/profiles/text/t19007_in.pdf]</ref>
