{{Evidence law}}
In [[law]], a '''foundation''' is sufficient preliminary [[evidence (law)|evidence]] of the [[Authentication (law)|authenticity]] and [[relevance (law)|relevance]] for the [[admissible evidence|admission]] of material evidence in the form of exhibits or [[testimony]] of [[witness]]es.  [[Materiality (law)|Material]] evidence is important evidence that may serve to determine the outcome of a case.  Exhibits include [[real evidence]], illustrative evidence, [[demonstrative evidence]], and [[documentary evidence]].  The type of preliminary evidence necessary to lay the proper foundation depends on the form and type of material evidence offered.

The lack of foundation is a valid [[objection (law)|objection]] that an [[adverse party]] may raise during [[trial (law)|trial]].

