{{Infobox language |name=Frafra |nativename=Gurenɛ |states=[[Ghana]], [[Burkina Faso]] |ethnicity=[[Frafra people]] |speakers={{sigfig|715,000|2}}<ref>Excluding ?30,000 Nabit and ?100,000 Talni</ref> |date=2003 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Gur languages|Gur]] |fam4=Northern |fam5=[[Oti–Volta languages|Oti–Volta]] |fam6=Mooré–Dagbani |fam7=Mooré |dia1=Gurenɛ |dia2=Nankani |dia3=Booni |iso3=gur |glotto=fare1241 |glottorefname=Farefare }}
'''Frafra''' or Farefare, also known as '''Gurenɛ''', is the language of the [[Frafra people]] of northern Ghana, particularly the [[Upper East Region]], and southern Burkina Faso. It is a national language of Ghana, and is closely related to [[Dagomba language|Dagbani]] and other languages of Northern [[Ghana]], and also related to [[Mossi language|Mossi]], also known as Mooré, the national language of Burkina Faso.
Frafra consists of three principal dialects, Gurenɛ (also written ''Gudenne, Gurenne, Gudeni, Zuadeni''), Nankani (''Naani, Nankanse, Ninkare''), and Booni. [[Nabit language|Nabit]] and [[Talni language|Talni]] have been mistakenly reported to be Frafra dialects.<ref>[http://www-01.sil.org/iso639-3/cr_files/2015-014.pdf ISO change request]</ref>
==Bibliography== *M.E. Kropp Dakubu, S. Awinkene Antintono, and E. Avea Nsoh, ''A Gurenɛ–English Dictionary and accompanying English–Gurenɛ Glossary''
