{{Infobox journal | title = Philological Quarterly | cover = | editor = Eric Gidal | discipline = [[Medieval studies]], literature | abbreviation = Philol. Q. | publisher = [[University of Iowa]], Department of English | country = United States | frequency = Quarterly | history = 1922-present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://english.uiowa.edu/pq/ | link1 = http://english.uiowa.edu/pq/abstracts/index.shtml | link1-name = Online abstracts | link2 = | link2-name = | JSTOR = | OCLC = 1762267 | LCCN = 27013435 | CODEN = | ISSN = 0031-7977 | eISSN = }} The '''''Philological Quarterly''''' is a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] covering research on [[Medieval literature|medieval European]] and [[History of modern literature|modern literature]] and culture. It was established in 1922 by [[Hardin Craig]].<ref>John C. Gerber, Carolyn B. Brown, James Kaufmann. ''A pictorial history of the University of Iowa.'' University of Iowa Press, 2005. Page 110.</ref> The inaugural issue of the journal was made available at sixty cents per copy and included articles on [[Chaucer]], [[Henry Fielding]], and [[Shakespeare]], among others. [[Berthold Ullman]] served with three colleagues on the original board of associate editors.<ref>"Front Matter," ''Philological Quarterly'' 1 (1922).</ref> Bill Kupersmith guided the journal through disciplinary reorganizations and changing academic norms during his thirty-year service as editor of the journal.<ref>[https://english.uiowa.edu/philological-quarterly/editorial-statement ''Editorial Statement'']</ref>
