{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox academic | caption = Rimma Komina | name = Rimma Komina | image = Photo_of_Rimma_Komina.jpg | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1926|05|30}} | birth_place = Zlatoust, [[Chelyabinsk Oblast|Chelyabinskaya Oblast']], [[USSR]] | death_date = {{Death date|df=yes|1995|10|12}} | death_place = [[Perm]], Russia | region = | occupation = | main_interests = [[Linguistics]] | alma_mater = Faculty of Philology, [[Moscow State University]] (1949) | doctoral_advisor = | awards = | website = }}
'''Rimma Vasilyevna Komina ''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|Ри́мма Васи́льевна Кóмина}}, {{IPA-ru|ˈrʲimə vɐˈsiljʲɪvnə ˈkomʲɪnə}}) was a Soviet and Russian specialist in [[literary criticism]], Doctor of Philology, professor (1985), dean of the philological faculty at [[Perm State University]] (1977–1982), the author of [[handbook]] "Contemporary [[Russian literature|Soviet literature]]" (1984), one of the key people in cultural life in [[Perm]] in the 1970s and 1980s. Her famous students are Jury Belikov<ref>[[:ru:Беликов, Юрий Александрович|Jury Belikov at Russian Wikipedia]]</ref> and [[Boris Kondakov]].
