'''Shrikrishna Janardan Joshi''' (1915–1989) was a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] novelist from [[Maharashtra]], [[India]].

In his writings, he harshly depicted [[Pune]], where he lived,  as a hub of [[Brahmin]] orthodoxy,.  He wrote several novels,  short stories, and essays, including award-winning novel ''Anandi Gopal'', which is a fictional account of the life of [[Anandi Gopal Joshi]]. The novel was later adapted into an award-winning play [[Anandi Gopal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-UjZlNCh-qwC&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=Shrikrishna+Janardan+Joshi&source=bl&ots=r1CjzUTi5K&sig=BNprtZVamtksdWDKM4Gw1Got9ZY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie3-3MseDVAhXFLFAKHfpMDYAQ6AEIWjAO#v=onepage&q=Shrikrishna+Janardan+Joshi&f=false|title=Making India: Colonialism, National Culture, and the Afterlife of Indian English Authority|first=Makarand R.|last=Paranjape|date=3 September 2012|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|accessdate=18 August 2017|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tnmgc.com/gomu.php?menu=3&id=203|title=Dr Anandibai Gopalrao Joshi|website=www.tnmgc.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>

He also authored a biography of R. D. Karve titled ' Raghunathachi Bakhar '.

